South African journalist

00:48:30.950 --> 00:48:34.570
who wrote a lot about the emperor.

00:48:34.570 --> 00:48:38.950
The story and relations with
Britain and Bath were not over.

00:48:38.950 --> 00:48:42.870
In the mid '50s, he
came back to Bath

00:48:42.870 --> 00:48:44.710
to be made free man of the city.

00:48:44.710 --> 00:48:47.840 position:56%
We have this quaint thing in Britain
where you have these things --

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:51.080
where you can be recognized
to be a free man of the city.

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:52.730
In London, it means
you can drive cattle

00:48:52.730 --> 00:48:55.040
across the Thames on a bridge.

00:48:55.040 --> 00:48:58.350
And if you're caught for any
dismeanor, you can be hanged

00:48:58.350 --> 00:49:00.520
with a silken cord
instead of a rope.

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:03.280
[Laughter] So it's quite
good being a free man.

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:05.090
Anyway, so he was a
free man of Bath;

00:49:05.090 --> 00:49:08.790
this time big state
reception, huge turnout.

00:49:08.790 --> 00:49:12.780
He gave these elephant
tusks to the city.

00:49:12.780 --> 00:49:17.060
Unfortunately, they were
stolen a couple years later.

00:49:17.060 --> 00:49:21.290
Fairfield House is still -- he
gave to the people of Bath in 1958.

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:23.630
It's still being use
as a community center.

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:28.320
And of course, he didn't
forget the people of Bath.

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:33.270
This is Fairfield Palace
in Debre Zeyit,

00:49:33.270 --> 00:49:35.940
which he named after
the house in Bath.

00:49:39.340 --> 00:49:42.610
And this is a picture I found
not long before his death

00:49:42.610 --> 00:49:43.980
at Fairfield House.

00:49:43.980 --> 00:49:47.980
Of course, those of you who
know the history, 40 years on,

00:49:47.980 --> 00:49:49.590
things were very different.

00:49:49.590 --> 00:49:58.450
And eventually, after being
murdered by the dirge in 1975,

00:49:58.450 --> 00:50:02.130
after the dirge had deposed,
and a few years later,

00:50:02.130 --> 00:50:06.430 position:56%
the emperor's buried in Holy Trinity
Cathedral, which he'd completed

00:50:06.430 --> 00:50:10.100
as a monument to his
victory over the Italians.

00:50:10.100 --> 00:50:12.830
So in terms of my story,
his time in exile,

00:50:12.830 --> 00:50:16.360
in some ways you could say it's
fitting that he is laid to rest

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:20.130 position:56%
at this place, which symbolizes one
of his defining moments of his life.

00:50:20.130 --> 00:50:24.250
Plus in the lead at the top, there
is a photograph of the League

00:50:24.250 --> 00:50:28.440
of Nation's speech and debate.

00:50:28.440 --> 00:50:33.310
So this exile period, this time of
fighting the Italians, was very,

00:50:33.310 --> 00:50:37.320
very important in his life, I
submit, and is therefore worthy

00:50:37.320 --> 00:50:40.920
of just thinking more than
he went to Geneva and Bath

00:50:40.920 --> 00:50:42.560
where he was cold for four years.

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:45.100
So that's what I tried to
do, ladies and gentlemen.

00:50:45.100 --> 00:50:49.510
So please, if you've got
any questions, please do.

00:50:49.510 --> 00:50:54.510
