00:50:58.350 --> 00:50:59.670
I hope it's not too difficult.

00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:01.470
You know, that's -- [laughs]

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:14.310
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:51:14.310 --> 00:51:16.110
Ah, well --

00:51:16.110 --> 00:51:20.270
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:51:20.270 --> 00:51:24.000
Yes; well, I mean, there are
some missing holes in the story,

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.570
but basically I've seen
some of the Cabinet papers

00:51:26.570 --> 00:51:30.980
for the discussions they had
when Mussolini declared war

00:51:30.980 --> 00:51:32.280
and the time running up to that.

00:51:32.280 --> 00:51:36.240
And they analyzed would the emperor
gain support from the patriots

00:51:36.240 --> 00:51:38.280
and from the people back home?

00:51:38.280 --> 00:51:40.290
What -- how should we support him?

00:51:40.290 --> 00:51:43.770 position:56%
By this time, you're right, Eden was
back in the Cabinet by this time.

00:51:43.770 --> 00:51:47.420 position:56%
And I don't know the answer to that,

00:51:47.420 --> 00:51:50.910
because I haven't seen
anything that said specifically.

00:51:50.910 --> 00:51:54.820
The Emperor said that he had
been promised modern weapons,

00:51:54.820 --> 00:51:59.430
and that he would be supported
very quickly to go back.

00:51:59.430 --> 00:52:01.970
In the end, he ended
up nine months waiting.

00:52:01.970 --> 00:52:06.640
And it was only sort of facilitated

00:52:06.640 --> 00:52:11.380
where Eden himself would had been
promoted again the Cabinet went

00:52:11.380 --> 00:52:15.980
to Khartoum, and basically pushed
the deal that led to the invasion.

00:52:15.980 --> 00:52:19.460
So there were still factions
in the British government.

00:52:19.460 --> 00:52:24.360
There was still opposition in
Africa among the British diplomats.

00:52:24.360 --> 00:52:25.870
Some of them didn't want
the emperor to come back.

00:52:25.870 --> 00:52:29.850 position:56%
And, of course, as we saw -- I mean,
this is not the subject of today,

00:52:29.850 --> 00:52:33.300
but more British sort of
government to-ing and fro-ing,

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:37.360
they really having in
their own eyes liberated --

00:52:37.360 --> 00:52:38.920
or helped to liberate Addis Ababa.

00:52:38.920 --> 00:52:41.840
They wanted to carry
on and run the place.

00:52:41.840 --> 00:52:46.510
And the emperor had to
fight them not literally --

00:52:46.510 --> 00:52:58.110
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:52:58.110 --> 00:52:59.410
Yes, they did.

00:52:59.410 --> 00:53:01.240
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:53:01.240 --> 00:53:03.480
Yes; it was British self-interest.

00:53:03.480 --> 00:53:06.840
Churchill wanted to send him
to cause trouble for Mussolini.

00:53:06.840 --> 00:53:08.320
He saw this was a way of doing it.

00:53:08.320 --> 00:53:12.020
Yes; so this was a feature
for the next two years.

00:53:12.020 --> 00:53:16.360
And this in fact led really why
the Ethiopian policy went much more

00:53:16.360 --> 00:53:18.490
towards the United States
in subsequent years.

00:53:18.490 --> 00:53:20.960
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:53:20.960 --> 00:53:22.260
Yes.

00:53:22.260 --> 00:53:25.090
&gt;&gt; My question is basically
the same, you know,

00:53:25.090 --> 00:53:29.260
whether there had been any
negotiation regarding the ultimate

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:32.650
invasion while he was
still [inaudible]?

00:53:32.650 --> 00:53:35.310
&gt;&gt; Keith Bowers: Well, I mean, in
the end, it was done quite quickly,

00:53:35.310 --> 00:53:39.510
but he thought they weren't --
maybe weren't going to send him.

00:53:39.510 --> 00:53:44.030
He did say to Sylvia Pankhurst at
one stage, "What are they doing?

00:53:44.030 --> 00:53:45.330
Why are they delaying?

00:53:45.330 --> 00:53:46.680
Why won't they send me?"

00:53:46.680 --> 00:53:50.260
And later, Sylvia Pankhurst said
-- she wrote an article saying,

00:53:50.260 --> 00:53:55.210
"I have to protect the emperor
from his protectors now."

00:53:55.210 --> 00:53:57.010
Yes.

00:53:57.010 --> 00:54:10.100
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:54:10.100 --> 00:54:11.480
Sorry; missed some of that.

00:54:11.480 --> 00:54:13.280
Is that --

00:54:13.280 --> 00:54:34.040
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:54:34.040 --> 00:54:35.690
Yes; it was to appease Mussolini.

00:54:35.690 --> 00:54:38.040
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:54:38.040 --> 00:54:39.770
Well, you could argue that.

00:54:39.770 --> 00:54:42.190
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:54:42.190 --> 00:54:45.190
Yes; you could make that case.

00:54:45.190 --> 00:54:46.860
You could make that case.

00:54:46.860 --> 00:54:49.890
&gt;&gt; Okay, thank you.

00:54:49.890 --> 00:54:51.190
&gt;&gt; Keith Bowers: There
was a tremendous amount

00:54:51.190 --> 00:54:52.490
of appeasing, of course.

00:54:52.490 --> 00:54:54.220
Yes; and I think that
the actual decision

00:54:54.220 --> 00:54:57.570
to recognize Italy's occupation,
that was a betrayal, definitely,

00:54:57.570 --> 00:55:00.490
when they said, "Well,
you know, let's move on."

00:55:00.490 --> 00:55:02.300
But it was different times.

00:55:02.300 --> 00:55:03.700
They were frightened
of war in Europe,

00:55:03.700 --> 00:55:05.300
and it was a frightening
war, as we saw.

00:55:05.300 --> 00:55:08.220
So no wonder they were
-- you have to try

00:55:08.220 --> 00:55:09.540
and understand it from
their point of new.

00:55:09.540 --> 00:55:12.500
I'm not justifying it, but
I'm saying they were trying

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:14.090
to make political calculations.

00:55:14.090 --> 00:55:17.450
And in the end, even though public
opinion was very pro Haile Selassie

00:55:17.450 --> 00:55:21.910 position:56%
at the beginning, they began more
and more to be worried about Europe,

00:55:21.910 --> 00:55:23.660
and Africa then seemed far away.

00:55:23.660 --> 00:55:26.770
So British public opinion wasn't --

00:55:26.770 --> 00:55:30.390
in some ways, the emperor was
becoming a little bit forgotten.

00:55:30.390 --> 00:55:32.930
And maybe if Mussolini hadn't
have come back into the war,

00:55:32.930 --> 00:55:34.520
he would never would have
come back to Ethiopia.

00:55:34.520 --> 00:55:41.950
&gt;&gt; During his life, did the British
government ever make a formal

00:55:41.950 --> 00:55:45.510
apology to Selassie
[laughter] [inaudible]?

00:55:45.510 --> 00:55:50.540
[ Background Talking ]

00:55:50.540 --> 00:55:51.840
&gt;&gt; Keith Bowers: No.

00:55:51.840 --> 00:55:54.950
[Laughter] I mean,
there were factions --

00:55:54.950 --> 00:55:59.730
as we said, there were
factions in the government.

00:55:59.730 --> 00:56:04.530
They felt they were
pursuing the right policy.

00:56:04.530 --> 00:56:08.710
And they would also point out and
say, "Well, didn't we supply troops

00:56:08.710 --> 00:56:12.000
and actually get rid of
the Italians in the end?"

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.920
But no, we're not talking
about principle here,

00:56:14.920 --> 00:56:19.510
we're talking about can do
politics, yes, that's --

00:56:19.510 --> 00:56:49.180
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:56:49.180 --> 00:56:50.590
Not very much.

00:56:50.590 --> 00:56:53.490
No, not very much, no.

00:56:53.490 --> 00:56:54.790
Later, they did.

00:56:54.790 --> 00:56:57.110
Of course, you know, the
current queen was quite close

00:56:57.110 --> 00:57:00.910
to His Imperial Majesty
and visited Ethiopia.

00:57:00.910 --> 00:57:04.830
And when he came back in 1954,
he stayed at Buckingham Palace,

00:57:04.830 --> 00:57:09.590
which was rather contrast
to how he turned up in 1936.

00:57:09.590 --> 00:57:18.070
But no I think even in 1924 when
he came on a grand European tour,

00:57:18.070 --> 00:57:21.440
the then king was a little bit
sniffy about receiving him or not.

00:57:21.440 --> 00:57:24.340
There was quite a lot of
racism -- let's not cut a --

00:57:24.340 --> 00:57:27.460
beat around the bush, there
was quite a lot of racism

00:57:27.460 --> 00:57:32.010
in the Foreign Office and in
sort of establishment circles,

00:57:32.010 --> 00:57:35.350
not just towards Ethiopia,
but towards, you know,

00:57:35.350 --> 00:57:38.510
anybody who was not from
Europe, I'm ashamed to say, so --

00:57:38.510 --> 00:57:47.050
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:57:47.050 --> 00:57:51.170
No. I mean, he wrote to
the king there in 1939.

00:57:51.170 --> 00:57:53.340
I've seen, again, at the archives

00:57:53.340 --> 00:57:57.060
in queue the diplomats have a big
debate about how should we reply

00:57:57.060 --> 00:57:59.270
to this letter, because the
King didn't reply; you know,

00:57:59.270 --> 00:58:01.200
the Foreign Office mandarins.

00:58:01.200 --> 00:58:04.720
And some factions said,
"Well, we can't --

00:58:04.720 --> 00:58:06.020
you know, who does he think he is?

00:58:06.020 --> 00:58:07.900
We can't let him think
he can get back his power

00:58:07.900 --> 00:58:09.900
on French and British bayonets."

00:58:09.900 --> 00:58:13.700
That is what someone said.

00:58:13.700 --> 00:58:19.380
So they did eventually try
and help him with his funding,

00:58:19.380 --> 00:58:20.970
because they didn't
want the embarrassment

00:58:20.970 --> 00:58:23.160
of the emperor going bankrupt.

00:58:23.160 --> 00:58:24.460
That was one of the features.

00:58:24.460 --> 00:58:25.760
I haven't really gone into it.

00:58:25.760 --> 00:58:27.200 position:56%
They were short of ready cash to pay

00:58:27.200 --> 00:58:29.080
for the household bills
and everything.

00:58:29.080 --> 00:58:34.790 position:56%
They did find a benefactor who gave,
I think it was 2,500 pounds a year,

00:58:34.790 --> 00:58:36.900
which is not a bad
sum in those days.

00:58:36.900 --> 00:58:39.470 position:56%
There was then a squabble within the
British establishment as to whether

00:58:39.470 --> 00:58:42.550
that should be subject to tax.

00:58:42.550 --> 00:58:46.190
The mysterious benefactor, Sir
William Collier, then collapsed

00:58:46.190 --> 00:58:47.800
and died of a heart
attack on a train.

00:58:47.800 --> 00:58:52.400
And there was another
[inaudible] over whether his legacy

00:58:52.400 --> 00:58:55.890
to the emperor was then
subject to more death tax.

00:58:55.890 --> 00:58:59.390
I mean, it was quite
extraordinary, really, the --

00:58:59.390 --> 00:59:01.760
he was spied on by
the tax authorities.

00:59:01.760 --> 00:59:07.820
And so I would say
no, I think we have

00:59:07.820 --> 00:59:12.290
to understand he preoccupation
wars with the rise of Nazism.

00:59:12.290 --> 00:59:15.960
You know, people quite
understandably, in some ways,

00:59:15.960 --> 00:59:18.960 position:56%
were not frequently straight, you
know, and the policy of appeasement,

00:59:18.960 --> 00:59:21.670
as we know, turned out
to be an utter failure.

00:59:21.670 --> 00:59:27.500
So no, I don't think it's --

00:59:27.500 --> 00:59:29.910
I think the story of his exile
really you could say I think the

00:59:29.910 --> 00:59:33.220
British people come out of it
pretty well in favoring Ethiopia

00:59:33.220 --> 00:59:36.210
and justice, international justice.

00:59:36.210 --> 00:59:39.490
British government was
sort of comme ci, comme ca,

00:59:39.490 --> 00:59:41.510
I think we could probably say.

